mineMS2: Annotation of spectral libraries with exact fragmentation patterns

Alexis Delabrière, Coline Gianfrotta and Etienne Thévenot

2025-02-08

1 Introduction

This vignette describes the features of the mineMS2 package to generate and explore fragmentation patterns in a collection from MS/MS spectra. The companion vignette (mineMS2_coupling-to-gnps) further presents the coupling of mineMS2 with GNPS to focus on patterns that best explain components of the molecular network.

1.1 Data

The data set included in the package, which is used in both vignettes, consists of 51 spectra from the untargeted study of the secondary metabolism of Penicillium nordicum (Hautbergue et al. 2019).

1.2 Installation

The package mineMS2 is available at the GitHub repository from the Odiscé team:

if (!require(devtools)) install.packages(devtools)
if (!require(mineMS2)) install_github("odisce/mineMS2")
library(mineMS2)

2 Loading the collection of MS/MS spectra

The ms2Lib class is used throughout the workflow to store the spectra data and metadata, the m/z differences, the fragmentation graphs, and the patterns.

The ms2Lib constructor function takes the collection of MS/MS spectra as input either:

  • as the name of a single mgf file containing all spectra

  • as a vector of the individual mgf file names

  • as the name of the directory containing the individual spectra stored as mgf files

  • as a list of Spectrum2 objects (from the MSnbase package).

Supplementary metadata about the spectra (such as the molecule names, or their elemental formulas) can also be provided as a csv file. These metadata are not used in the computations (m/z differences, fragmentation graphs, frequent patterns) but can be displayed in the plot titles (see below). The csv file of metadata should contain as many rows as spectra. By default, spectra are associated to rows in the same order, but if the dataset consists of individual spectrum files, it is possible to match each spectrum to a specific row by using a column file.

# Finding the spectra data
pnordicum_mgf.c <- system.file("dataset/dda_msms_pnordicum.mgf",
                             package = "mineMS2")

# Supplementary information
pnordicum_metadata.c <- system.file("dataset/dda_msms_pnordicum_supp.csv",
                                  package = "mineMS2")
pnordicum_metadata.df <- read.table(pnordicum_metadata.c,header = TRUE, sep = ";",
                                  encoding = "utf-8", quote = "") 
head(pnordicum_metadata.df)

Metadata (e.g. m/z and retention time) can be linked to the IDs of the spectra as follows:

pnordicum_metadata.df <- getInfo(pnordicum.msl,"S")
# dataframe storing all the information about the spectra
pnordicum_ids.c <- paste(paste("mz",pnordicum_metadata.df[,"mz"]),
                       paste("rt",pnordicum_metadata.df[,"rt"]), sep = "_")
pnordicum.msl <- setIds(pnordicum.msl,pnordicum_ids.c)

2.1 Visualizing the spectra

Each spectrum can be displayed with the plot method by using its ID:

plot(pnordicum.msl, "S14")

Here the S14 index refers to the 14th spectrum of the collection (from aurantiomide C; precursor m/z 341.1605 and retention time 20.09).

getInfo(pnordicum.msl, "S14")[, c("Name", "mz", "corrected_rt")]

ms2_spectra.ls <- mm2Spectra(pnordicum.msl)
ms2_spectrum.ms2 <- ms2_spectra.ls[[14]]

3 Computing the fragmentation graphs

3.1 m/z differences

The first step of the mineMS2 algorithm, discretizeMzDifferences, computes the m/z differences between the peaks in each spectrum and discretizes (or aligns) them for the whole spectra collection (so that common m/z differences between spectra have the same value throughout the collection). Note that these m/z differences include not only the neutral losses but also differences between ions that belong to distinct fragmentation paths of the precursor.

This step is very important, as it determines the initial set of fragmentation graphs. The main parameters are listed below:

  • ppm: The accuracy of the mass spectrometer in ppm used to determine the bandwidth of the kernel density estimation (default: 7)

  • dmz: The minimum deviation used for bandwidth (in Da; default: 0.002)

  • count: The minimum number of spectra in which a m/z difference needs to be present to be considered as frequent (default: 2)

  • precPpm: The ppm tolerance used to match the precursor (default: 20). The precPpm and precDmz arguments are used to find a peak corresponding to the precursor on the MS/MS spectra. If it is not present, an artificial peak is added

  • precDmz: The minimum tolerance in Da used to match the precursor (default: 0.02)

  • maxFrags: only the maxFrags most intense peaks will be considered to build the graph (should be at most 20 to be done in reasonable time; default: 15)

  • atoms: list of possible atoms for formula generation, along with their respective maximum number (default: list("C"=16,"H"=50,"N"=10,"O"=15,"Cl"=2,"S"=2,"P"=2))

  • heteroAtoms: Indicates whether hetero atoms (P,S,Cl) should be used when generating formula for m/z differences (default: TRUE)

  • limMzFormula: the range of m/z difference values for which formulas will be searched (default: c(14.5, 200)).

    • For each m/z difference in the range defined by limMzFormula, possible formulas are generated, using a decomposition of possible atoms given by the argument atoms. If no formula is found, the m/z difference is discarded

    • For m/z differences higher than the limMzFormula upper limit, no formula is generated but the m/z difference is kept

pnordicum.msl <- discretizeMzDifferences(pnordicum.msl,
                                       ppm = 15,
                                       dmz = 0.007,
                                       count = 2,
                                       precPpm = 20,
                                       precDmz = 0.02,
                                       maxFrags = 15,
                                       heteroAtoms = TRUE,
                                       limMzFormula = c(14.5, 200))

After this step, the list of discretized m/z differences labels may be extracted:

head(mzDiffTable(pnordicum.msl))
##   lab       mz    mzmin    mzmax count formula
## 1   1 16.02890 16.02424 16.03357    22     CH4
## 2   2 17.02649 17.02182 17.03115    20     H3N
## 3   3 18.01053 18.00586 18.01520    84     H2O
## 4   4 23.99999 23.99532 24.00466    11      C2
## 5   5 26.01568 26.01102 26.02035     6    C2H2
## 6   6 28.03133 28.02667 28.03600    13    C2H4

Each row of this table corresponds to one discretized m/z difference, with:

  • mz: mean value among the occurences in the spectra collection

  • mzmin: minimum value

  • mzmax: maximum value

  • count: number of occurrences

  • formula: the possible formula(s), if calculated

The information about a specific m/z difference can be directly accessed with:

getInfo(pnordicum.msl, "L187")
##      lab      mz    mzmin    mzmax count
## L187 187 147.068 147.0633 147.0726    41
##                                                                                                                                               formula
## L187 C4H9O3N3|C2H14O4NP|C3H10N5P|CH13O3N3S|C9H9ON|CH15ON3P2|HO7Cl|C6H13ONS|C5H9O4N|C6H5N5|C4H10ON3P|H14N5SP|C3H17ONS2|H5ON9|C3H9O2N5|H9O6N3|C2H13O4NS

3.2 Fragmentation graphs

The step of discretization also builds the fragmentation graph for each spectrum, i.e. the directed acyclic graph (DAG) with the spectrum peaks as nodes and the frequent (discretized) m/z differences as edges. Each fragmentation graph can be plotted with the plot method in a static or dynamic way (tkplot argument set to FALSE or TRUE, respectively; default: FALSE).

plot(pnordicum.msl, "D14")

Here, the graph D14 corresponds to the spectrum S14.

4 Mining frequent fragmentation patterns

The next step consists in extracting the frequent subgraphs (i.e. the patterns) among the fragmentation graphs. The mineClosedSubgraphs method has two main parameters:

  • count: minimum number of spectra containing the pattern

  • sizeMin: minimum size of the pattern

Here we set sizeMin to 1 to include patterns containing a single m/z difference.

pnordicum.msl <- mineClosedSubgraphs(pnordicum.msl, count = 2, sizeMin = 1)
## Processing completed: 290 patterns mined.

5 Exploring the patterns

Spectra (S), m/z differences (L), fragmentation graphs (D), and patterns (P) are stored in the ms2Lib object with an ID starting with the corresponding upper case letter and followed by an integer index (e.g. S14, D14, L187). The findMz and select methods are designed to extract spectra, m/z differences, and patterns of interest. The plotPatterns methods can then be used to the patterns and associated spectra.

5.1 findMz: getting spectra or m/z differences close to a specific (precursor) m/z

findMz gets the IDs of spectra or m/z differences whose m/z (of the precursor ion in the case of spectra) is close to a specific value; it returns the character vector of corresponding IDs (starting with a S or an L, respectively).

  • Use case 1: Looking for spectra with precursor m/z value close to 147.0:
verrucolone_spectra.vc <- findMz(pnordicum.msl, 147.0, type = "S", ppm = 8, dmz = 0.2)
getInfo(pnordicum.msl, verrucolone_spectra.vc)
##    mz.precursor
## S3     147.0649
##                                                                                        file
## S3 C:/Users/et207099/AppData/Local/R/win-library/4.3/mineMS2/dataset/dda_msms_pnordicum.mgf
##    id      mz   rt group polarity id_file        Name formula corrected_rt
## S3  3 147.064 3.12     B      pos       3 Verrucolone C6H10O4         3.12
##    fungisporins N
## S3              3
  • Use case 2: Finding an m/z difference corresponding to phenylalanine:
phe_loss.c <- findMz(pnordicum.msl, type = "L", 147.05, dmz = 0.1)
getInfo(pnordicum.msl, phe_loss.c)
##      lab      mz    mzmin    mzmax count
## L187 187 147.068 147.0633 147.0726    41
##                                                                                                                                               formula
## L187 C4H9O3N3|C2H14O4NP|C3H10N5P|CH13O3N3S|C9H9ON|CH15ON3P2|HO7Cl|C6H13ONS|C5H9O4N|C6H5N5|C4H10ON3P|H14N5SP|C3H17ONS2|H5ON9|C3H9O2N5|H9O6N3|C2H13O4NS

5.2 select: getting patterns contained in specific spectra or including specific m/z differences

Based on the spectra (or m/z difference) indices selected above, the select method enable to retrieve the patterns that are included in all these spectra (or that contain the m/z differences); it returns a list of pattern indices for the query spectra (or m/z differences).

  • Use case 1: Patterns in the Verrucolone spectrum:
verrucolone_pattern.ls <- select(pnordicum.msl, verrucolone_spectra.vc, "P")
verrucolone_pattern.ls
## $S3

5.3 plotPatterns: visualizing the patterns

The plotPatterns method applied to a character vector of pattern indices displays for each pattern:

  • the graph of the pattern; the nodes of this graph are labeled with the sum of m/z differences from the root of the graph, along with the corresponding formula. The edges of the graph are labeled with the corresponding m/z differences, along with the formula. A formula in brackets indicates that several formulas are possible and the one with the closest mass is shown.

  • the spectra containing the pattern with colored peaks corresponding to nodes of the pattern

  • a list of supplementary information about these spectra

phe_pattern.c <- phe_patterns.ls[[phe_loss.c]][3]
plotPatterns(pnordicum.msl, phe_pattern.c, export_pdf = FALSE)
